$$, $$92e4071cc51cff25a9b5afc8d4e38e72131e730d90d0fffed75e339fc600f938$$, $${"A": "afc57ab6ba9201183524bf872dca723763aad7f81a77375538880e3674e24860", "C": "d4fdf923ba776b98bda680220afe7660b2fb7f78e25f4cb026ad0b29031d9620", "D": "12a859aa21beb8237fb563241fcf8367e127e404aded6bd8f1d6c16066416aba"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY26/USAF/FY26 Air Force Research and Development Test and Evaluation Vol III.pdf$$, 121, $$2026-05-07T23:57:02.622579+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0305114F$$, 2027, $$To support the Air Force worldwide flying mission, the Air Traffic Control and Landing System (ATCALS) program element funds research, development, and
management of fielded and emerging air traffic control communications, surveillance, automation, positioning, and precision approach and landing systems. ATCALS
programs are focused on development of technology and strategies to support Agile Combat Employment (ACE) adaptive basing and agile basing concepts of operation
as well as modernizing airfield operations to ensure enduring, resilient, efficient, and safe air operations. ATCALS also pursues opportunities in the organization, training,
and equipping of ATC associated career fields and any new civil ATCALS technologies that may have military utility.

 ATCALS currently includes three projects: Air Traffic Control (ATC) Future Technology (AFT), Multi-Function Tactical Radar System (MTRS), and Tactical ATC
 Operations System (TACOS).

 1. AFT is a multi-project program focused on identifying and documenting capability gaps and associated future technologies in multiple areas of aircraft launch and
 recovery for both fixed and expeditionary operations. These gaps and technologies will be outlined in a bridging strategy, capability-based assessments, and capability
 roadmaps.

 FY 2027 AFT research and development spans multiple projects that include the following:

 - The Small Footprint Precision Approach and Landing Capability (SF-PALC) effort aims to reduce the footprint, transport and set-up time for delivering instrument
 landing system capabilities in an Agile Combat Employment (ACE) Environment. SF-PALC researches multiple technologies including a traditional instrumented landing
 system (ILS) approach and a non-traditional tactical transponder approach.

 - The Flight Inspection Drone project manages the foreign comparative test of flight inspection drones against Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) and Air Force flight
 inspection requirements. The goal is to reduce flight inspections, fuel costs, and inspection time while also reducing exposure in a contested environment.

 As these and other technologies and architectures mature, any applicable fixed-base or deployable, ground-system upgrades will be coordinated and fielded
 concurrently with related manned and unmanned aircraft avionics capabilities as required. When implemented, these efforts will enable Department of War (DoW)
 aircraft to enhance safety, security, efficiency, and affordability of global flight operations.

Operational Systems Development
 2. The Multifunction Tactical Radar System (MTRS) will be capable of supporting Air Traffic Control (ATC) surveillance and communication, weather alerts, Unmanned
 Aircraft System (UAS) detection, and air battle management command control (BMC2) situational awareness. MTRS provides mobile ATC surveillance radar capability
 in an Agile Combat Operations (ACE) environment to replace the the unsupportable legacy (1970's-era) AN/MPN-14K. The last AN/MPN-14K will decommission in
 FY 2028. MTRS Initial Operational Capability (IOC) is anticipated in FY 2030. Two refurbished Air Traffic Control Navigation, Integration, and Coordination System
 (ATNAVICS) along with the three Africa Command (AFRICOM) Expeditionary Scalable MCRs will provide a limited material solution until MTRS IOC.

 3. The Tactical ATC Command and Control (C2) Operating Systems (TACOS) will automate, and display sensor feeds and includes the communication radios and voice
 switch needed by controllers to communicate to aircraft, host nations, and other agencies. TACOS will include the shelters, furniture, laptops, servers, software, power-
 supplies, and communications equipment needed for controllers to perform their mission in environments when existing infrastructure is damaged or does not exist.
 TACOS will include software interfaces with the greater Department of Air Force (DAF) Battle Network as well as appropriate C2 nodes for air battle management and
 counter-small UAS sensors and networks.

 This program element may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such program funds
 would be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program element 0605827F, 0605828F, 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605832F, 0605833F, 0605898F,
 0606398F.

 This program is in Budget Activity 7, Operational System Development because this budget activity includes development efforts to upgrade systems that have been
 fielded or have received approval for full rate production and anticipate production funding in the current or subsequent fiscal year.$$, $$To support the Air Force worldwide flying mission, the Air Traffic Control and Landing System (ATCALS) program element funds research, development, and
